{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12594"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12594"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.08,0.24,0.02,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41898"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5087"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44960"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41898"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his general practice with sudden loss of hearing in his left ear. He noticed this deafness when he woke up this morning. He has not had any similar experience before. For the last three hours he has been hearing buzzing sounds. He has no earache, ear discharge, fever, headache, vertigo and any other focal neurological symptoms. He denies any history of trauma and exposure to loud noises. He is fit with no significant medical history and does not take any medications. There is no family history of hearing impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 122/78 mmHg, pulse 70/min, temperature 36.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 12/min. Otoscopy of his left ear shows a small amount of earwax on the external auditory canal. The eardrum is visible with no signs of redness, perforation or discharge. Otoscopy of the right ear is normal. The Weber test lateralises to the right ear, and the Rinne test is positive. On field testing, he reports difficulty hearing conversational voice from his left ear at 15 cm away from himself. Hearing is grossly normal in right ear. No lymphadenopathy is found in the head and neck region. All testing for cranial nerves is normal.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High-dose corticosteroid","Docusate sodium ear drops","Pure-tone audiometric testing","Intratympanic steroid injection","Urgent MRI brain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem describes a classic case of sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSNHL). This is likely to be idiopathic, which is roughly 99% of all cases. With no other symptoms, this patient presents with sudden unilateral hearing loss which is sensorineural in nature as reflected by the Weber and Rinne tests. He does not take any medication which might be ototoxic and is physically fit otherwise. Awakening with a sudden hearing loss in this case strongly suggests SSNHL. This is defined as a \u2018hearing loss of 30 dB or more over at least three contiguous frequencies, over a period of 72 hours or less\u2019. However, when the clinical picture is clear, a clinical diagnosis can be made and proper treatment should be commenced as soon as possible. Permanent hearing loss is much more likely to occur if treatment is delayed. The first-line treatment of SSNHL is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose corticosteroid\u003C/strong\u003E, 1 mg/kg/day (to a maximum of 60 mg/day), for 5 days initially, then\u00a0the dose is reduced daily by 10 mg consecutively in the next 5 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocusate sodium ear drops\u003C/strong\u003E are the first-line treatment for symptomatic ear wax accumulation. However, a small amount of earwax observed during otoscopic examination is unlikely to cause sudden hearing loss to this magnitude.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure-tone audiometric testing\u003C/strong\u003E is required to establish a definitive diagnosis of SSNHL. However, when the clinical picture is clear and the diagnosis not in doubt, it is prudent to start treatment and this can be followed by the audiometry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratympanic steroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E is usually reserved for patients with SSNHL who respond poorly to oral steroids and recurrence with previous oral steroid therapy. It can also be first-line if there is contraindication to oral steroids such as brittle diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn urgent \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be done if a pathology arising from the brain is suspected such as an anterior inferior cerebellar artery stroke or vestibular schwannoma. These conditions are unlikely given the absence of other symptoms.\u00a0Nonetheless, to accurately rule them out, further non-urgent MRI brain is always done.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SSNHL has to be treated as soon as possible due to the possibility of permanent hearing loss.","Treatment with high-dose corticosteroid can be commenced before a definitive diagnosis is made."],"references":["Foden N, Mehta N, Joseph T. Sudden onset hearing loss. Aust J Gen Pract. 2013;42:641-4."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12594"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-26T15:43:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-26T15:43:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5087"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41898"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://ap